snippet.textDisplay: Can we just talk about the box and how it says "Dolby Surround"? The SNES can only produce stereo. How is that even possible?
snippet.textOriginal: Can we just talk about the box and how it says "Dolby Surround"? The SNES can only produce stereo. How is that even possible?

snippet.textDisplay: In layman's terms; old Dolby Surround was an encoding technology matrixed the 4 (or was it 3?) audio channels into the normal stereo jacks. When the jacks were plugged into a Dolby Surround decoder, the stereo signal would be decoded and the original channels would play. A more refined version of the analog system would later be used in a lot of PS2 games, since the PS2 could not do digital 5.1 in gameplay
snippet.textOriginal: In layman's terms; old Dolby Surround was an encoding technology matrixed the 4 (or was it 3?) audio channels into the normal stereo jacks. snippet.textDisplay: Hello, you! The composer says the song wasn't written for any particular reason. He was asked for songs to put into the Flintstones game, and this was one of them. The programmers used spare space on the ROM to fill it up with music for their jukebox. Other tracks he'd written were used for the game, but this wasn't suitable - but it was left on the game cartridge.
